Security Guide ‚Äî Brightlines Cart 0 About Us How it works Pricing Security Guide Contact Cart 0 About Us How it works Pricing Security Guide Contact Security Guide What steps can you take to protect yourself online? Minimize identifying info on public databases Public databases often provide an ongoing front for the exposure of personal identifying They are a common source of information for data brokers and people search Set up a post office box or a virtual mailbox: A USPS Post Office Box is relatively inexpensive but be aware that not all banks or services will accept PO A UPS Mailbox provides a physical address for greater Virtual PostMail or Traveling Mailbox can scan your mail and send you an electronic copy, and can shred your mail, Create an alternate phone number To limit how your contact information is exposed on the internet, consider setting up an intermediate phone number to share instead of providing your direct Use Google Voice for your alternate number you can connect it to an existing Gmail account or set up a new Select a number for your Google Then, forward calls received by Google Voice to your main number Calls and text from the Google Voice app ( Android iOS ) on your phone Be mindful of services such as WhatsApp and Signal, which use your phone number as Note: Be aware that some services may not accept a VoIP number such as Google Voice to link to your This is common among financial services to prevent Enhance email protection To enhance your privacy, we recommend using a public email account that forwards to your main email The public account can be used anywhere on the web: to log in to social media and accounts, and sign up for Do not use it as an inbox, but as a relay to forward email do not keep email in the This limits the exposure of your actual email account, making it harder to Here are a few common email providers, and how to set up forwarding for them: Set up forwarding from your Gmail Set up forwarding from your Yahoo! Mail Set up forwarding from your iCloud email Set up forwarding from your Microsoft email Strengthen account security Fundamental practices to securing online account security go a long way towards improving your overall security Strong passwords are important, but more critical is good credential hygiene: enabling two factor authentication where possible, minimizing password reuse with unique passwords, and changing passwords Implementing these practices can take time since they likely involve your accounts, either by turning on (Two Factor Authentication) or resetting your existing passwords (especially if you are currently passwords between accounts). While we recommend that all accounts have a unique password and , to make the process manageable we suggest starting with critical accounts, such as your primary email address and the recovery email for these Consider also accounts where you may have stored sensitive data, and once you feel comfortable doing these tasks with your critical accounts, expand it to your other accounts: Enable where Be sure to use an authenticator app we strongly recommend Authy to store and manage your authentication While other authenticator apps such as Google Authenticator and Microsoft Authenticator also work, Authy provides the advantage of being easy to migrate between This will keep you from needing to reconfigure your when you get a new We do not recommend using SMS messages for your method, if given the option, as these can easily be Set unique passwords that have not been used We suggest allowing your password manager to generate passwords for Password managers such as Dashlane or LastPass are very helpful tools for supporting We recommend paying for the premium versions of these tools since a subscription is needed to use the service app on multiple Close orphan accounts Orphan accounts are those that have been left inactive but not Orphaned accounts are vulnerable, as the passwords are likely simpler, and with less activity, you‚Äôre unlikely to notice an Depending on the data contained in the account, the outcome can be Here‚Äôs what you can do with any orphan accounts: Limit access to the account: Close the account if you no longer need it Strengthen the account‚Äôs security, in case you prefer to keep Specifically: Enable if available, and update with a robust password Change the login email address to your address (see above), using an active, secure email account as the recovery address Manage the content of the orphan account if you decide to keep Depending on the content, you have the following options: Change the privacy settings, if Delete content Magazine Curve Archive Ahead of the Curve Ahead of the Curve Test News Investing in lesbian and queer women‚Äôs culture About Launched in as Deneuve magazine, Curve has been America‚Äôs lesbian magazine for nearly three As Curve‚Äôs anniversary approached, founder Franco Stevens reimagined how Curve will serve lesbians and queer women in its next Her journey to this historic decision is captured in the documentary film Ahead of the Curve . Franco, along with a dynamic Advisory Council, started The Curve Foundation to empower the Curve Community ‚Äì lesbians, queer women, trans women, and people of all races, ages, and The Curve Foundation will spur active storytelling and dialogue around the Curve Community by supporting journalism inspired by the tradition of Curve magazine, investing in the next generation of intersectional leaders, and bolstering existing community archives as a resource to ensure LGBTQ+ women‚Äôs culture and history can be Franco reacquired Curve magazine and donated it to the Foundation so it can leverage the brand and amplify the Foundation‚Äôs Curve magazine is now a nonprofit project of The Curve We will regularly curate articles from the Curve Archive, filling a critical niche by providing a way to understand our history ‚Äì a portal into the lessons from our past that can inform our actions into the The Curve Foundation will bring the archive to life to provide context and a throughline between the critical conversations forming our movement in the and early and We are not accepting unsolicited submissions at this Mission Empower lesbian, queer women, trans women, and people to share our culture and our stories, connect with each other, and raise Vision A renaissance of journalists inspired by the tradition of Curve will be actively telling community stories and engaging in dialogue to connect and inspire, and to provide and find information about our community‚Äôs culture and About Support Resources News Notice: JavaScript is required for this Donate now ¬© The Curve Foundation , All rights Privacy Policy Join our email list Notice: JavaScript is required for this "cookieName":"wBounce","isAggressive":false,"isSitewide":true,"hesitation":"","openAnimation":false,"exitA
